@NODE "OVER"
@title "An Overview of DOSReqTools"
@{fg highlight}
DOSReqTools by BOTH Software
@{fg text}
 Until now, only programmers who have mastered C or other high level
 programming languages could use the power of Nico Francois' ReqTools.
 His requesters have become the defacto standard in the Amiga community.
 Now his requesters may be used by anyone who writes AmigaDOS scripts.
 
 DOSReqTools allows you to write complete installer scripts, including 
 on-line Help. 

 Other uses for DOSReqTools include automating your backup scripts and 
 system boot-up scripts.
 
 You can now include decision making abilities within an AmigaGuide 
 database. This database is an example. Your programs could actually 
 be installed from within the Guide Doc. Throughout this Manual, 
 you will see interactive examples of this facility. The syntax for
 calling your script from a label is:
@{fg fill}
       *{"label" SYSTEM "EXECUTE demo.overview"}
@{fg text}
                             @{"label" SYSTEM "EXECUTE demo.overview"}

 The requester will pop to the front screen, right on top of the
 AmigaGuide (or MultiView) screen. Can you see some possibilities here?
@{fg highlight}
          About using the demos from this manual:

      As long as the demos and this AmigaGuide database 
      are in the same  directory, the demos will pop up
      on the screen.
@{fg text}
 This manual is designed to help you learn how to use the various 
 requesters, not how to use AmigaDOS. It is assumed you have some 
 knowledge of DOS. There are plenty of interactive examples to help 
 you learn the syntax of the requesters.

 Each type of requester may be called with a variety of "arguments",
 like TITLE or BODY. These arguments are presented in each section
 of this manual that describes a requester. The sections begin with
 a complete list of the arguments that the requester can use. These 
 are @{"labels" link fake} that will direct you to an explaination of that argument.

 The Command Template for that requester is presented in each section.  

 We hope you find DOSReqTools useful. If Nico Francois updates 
 ReqTools, we will port the changes into DOSReqTools. 

 You will need a passing knowledge of templates to use the requesters.
 There are more that 40 demo scripts included. You can learn quickly 
 by studying them.
@ENDNODE

@NODE NEXT
@TITLE "Why did you write DOSReqTools? I hate DOS!!!"


 DOSReqTools is the first of a two part package. We want to give some
 programming power to DOS script writers. As implimented under 2.1 and
 3.0, DOS is not a functional programming language. It lacks most of the
 basic looping structures and just about anything else that would
 define it as a language. What DOS has going for it is that every Amiga
 has it built in, and it can be useful for limited functions.

 DOS is never going to be a real programming language. What we hope to do 
 is allow people who have not learned C to write functional, powerful
 scripts in a way that was not possible before.


 1 DOSReqTools adds several new extensions to DOS to allow manipulation
   of strings and filenames. It also adds the requesters to the DOS
   script writer's toolbox.

 2 The next part, MUInt, gives a script writer access to a definable
   MUI GUI. The GUI can have up to three PopASL filerequesters, a
   ListView, a scrolling textwindow, Radio buttons, Checkmark boxes,
   and any number of programmable buttons. The buttons, when pressed
   can execute any DOS command or DOS script.

   @{b}The GUI does not leave the screen until the QUIT button is pressed.@{ub}

   From the user's point of view, the GUI looks like any other GUI
   generated by MUIBuilder and driven by a C program.

   This system allows a programmer to quickly write a professional
   looking GUI for his application. Another use for MUInt is to
   write front ends for existing CLI-ONLY programs, thus allowing
   WorkBench users easy access to these executables.

   We rely heavily on user feedback for the development of these
   programs. If you have questions or would like to advance some 
   ideas, contact us.

   We are currently working a a new language for the Amiga called 
   COMAL. If this project interests you, please send Email to us.

   The DOSReqTools/MUInt package was written in the first part of 1995.
   Development stopped in March and the project was shelved for a bit. 
   It is now as good as it's gonna get, so I am releasing it. @{b}I would 
   like to caution you about some things you will find here.@{ub} 
 
 Some of the executables have Enforcer hits. Do not let this prevent 
 you from using the programs. The hits are not caused by illegal memory 
 access, but rather a deficiency in the Enforcer itself. Do not send me
 Email reporting Enforcer hits. I've already gone ten rounds with the
 beta testers over this. :)
 
 If you use the Installer.script, the Uninstall file will be placed in 
 RAM. Copy it to a place of safekeeping.
 
 I have tried my best to remove all references to "beta testers" from 
 these docs. If I missed something, please ignore it.
 
 I know that not all of the scripts in MUInt_prg_x are completely 
 functional. The scripts were written (and distributed) so you could 
 see how MUInt and DOSReqTools can be used in a wide variety of 
 applications. Some of these scripts use a configuration script to 
 customize the program to your system. The variables are written to 
 Env-Archive, so if you see some strange looking files in ENV:, you 
 know where they came from.
 
 I've spent a couple of days trying out the scripts in this package. I 
 think they all work as advertised. If not, just FLAME me. 

 You will need a good understanding of DOS to get the most from all 
 these programs. Try writing some simple scripts at first. If you have 
 some fun with all this and plan on using it in the future, I recommend 
 you make rtEZrequest and Advice resident. This will speed up many of your 
 scripts.

 I use a 40mzh, 030 A1200 with a 640X495 screen. I know that I have 
 formatted some of the docs to this screen size. If this causes you 
 some problems, please excuse me.

 As I mentioned before, Will and I are writing COMAL for the Amiga. 
 We wrote MUInt and DOSReqTools so that COMAL would have access to 
